# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcott-house
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] The house was built in about 1720 but the facade and porch were added later.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] The design involved a symmetrical main frontage with nine bays: the central section features a porch with four Tuscan columns.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] The building was the seat of local government for the Barnes Urban District from 1895 to 1932 and then of the Municipal Borough of Barnes from 1932 until 1940, when it was damaged by wartime bombing.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] The house's 7 acres (2.8 ha) of grounds have now been completely built over, and the building itself has been converted to commercial office space.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] The exterior is still similar to what it was in two oil paintings that J.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] Turner's two paintings were made for William Moffatt, whose house it then was.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] *Mortlake Terrace: Early Summer Morning* (1826) is in the Frick Collection, New York.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] It was shown in the Royal Academy exhibition of 1826 where it was praised for its "lightness and simplicity".
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] *Mortlake Terrace* (1827) is in the National Gallery of Art, Washington D.C.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] The Museum of London holds a wood engraving of people at The Limes, as it was then called, watching the Oxford and Cambridge Boat Race.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] *The Limes – Mortlake: 1872* is taken from *London: A Pilgrimage* by Blanchard Jerrold and Gustave Doré, 1872.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] Jerrold describes how "the towing paths presented to the view of the more fortunate people upon the private river-side terraces, a mixed population ..." The house was, at the time, the residence of a Mr Marsh Nelson.
[src:alcott-house/123-mortlake-high-street] The house's former residents include the Franks, a family of Jewish merchant bankers; Lady Byron, widow of the poet; the educational philanthropist Quintin Hogg; and Garnet Wolseley, 1st Viscount Wolseley, who lived there from 1874 to 1875 and later became Commander-in-Chief of the Forces.
[src:alcott-house/14-the-terrace-barnes] Dame Ninette de Valois (1898–2001), dancer, teacher, choreographer, and director of classical ballet, lived there from 1962 to 1982.
[src:alcott-house/14-the-terrace-barnes] A blue plaque is fixed to the front of the house.
[src:alcott-house/18-station-road-barnes] It was home to the novelist Henry Fielding in about 1750, for which there is a blue plaque on the facade.
[src:alcott-house/18-station-road-barnes] Field Marshal James O'Hara, 2nd Baron Tyrawley moved there in 1770.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:alcott-house/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] He became a vegetarian as a young man through reading the work of T.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] Bailey Walker and joined the Vegetarian Society in 1877.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] He worked as an analytical chemist in Manchester and for James Woolley, Sons and Co., manufacture chemists.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] Duncan had studied with Carl Remigius Fresenius.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] He was also a Fellow of the Chemical Society.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] In 1884, Duncan authored a pamphlet *The Chemistry of Foods*.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] It was republished as *The Chemistry of Food and Nutrition* by the Vegetarian Society in 1905.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] Forward noted that Duncan had given "valuable aid to the Vegetarian Society in connection with the chemistry of food, and has contributed many useful essays and papers on the subject".
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] Duncan was on the executive committee of the Vegetarian Society in 1880 and later served as a vice-president.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] In 1899, Duncan commented that "a grain of wheat contains everything that is required for nutrition and these constituents are in the right proportion, so that were it necessary we could live on wheatmeal bread and water alone".
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] He later moved to New South Wales, Australia but remained in contact with vegetarians in England and was an officer for the Vegetarian Society in 1935.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] He married Annie Margaret Allison in 1890.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] They had two children: Frank and Phyllis.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] Duncan died in Punchbowl, New South Wales in 1946, aged 90.
[src:alcott-house/a-w-duncan] He was privately cremated at Rockwood crematorium.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] The **A307 road** runs 13.2 miles (21.2 km) through SW London and NW Surrey.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] It is primary at the north-east end; the remainder is non-primary, generally superseded in the mid-twentieth century in two stages by newer alignments of the Portsmouth Road, the Kingston bypass and Esher bypass of the A3, which runs along a slightly oblique axis.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] It then runs towards Richmond upon Thames through the west of Kew.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] At the junction with the A316 in Richmond it becomes a non-primary A-road through the town centre then heads through Petersham where for fewer than 100 metres it kinks west and then travels south through Ham.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] A B-class road, the B353, leaves the A307 in Kew and runs around the town centre and up Richmond Hill and by-passing Richmond, before rejoining the A307 at Petersham.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] It bisects the north of the town, before becoming the western half of the one-way system in Kingston upon Thames.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] Here it is briefly merged with the A308.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] It leads south to the northern end of the A240, for 200m travels west to the River Thames, and resuming south becomes at last the old version of the Portsmouth Road (which is also its name here).
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] It runs next to the River Thames, heading through Surbiton.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] It passes a junction with the A243, shortly before exiting the borough at Seething Wells there next to Long Ditton.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] The road now follows an almost straight south-west course (losing the Thames, which at Thames Ditton curves away to the north).
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] It passes through Hinchley Wood, crossing the A309 at the Scilly Isles roundabout.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] The A307 follows the old route of the Portsmouth Road, particularly the section south of the junction with the A308.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] Robert Clive ("Clive of India") diverted it slightly believing it ran too close to his house at Claremont, the landscape garden of which remains and which it still borders.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] A watchman's box that also served as a village lock-up, dating from 1787, is next to the Fox & Duck in Petersham.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] Responsibility for the north section, Kew Road and Richmond Road, passed from the crown to the Commissioner of Works under the Crown Lands Act 1851.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] The A307 was closed during 1979 and 1980 for a total of almost 18 months by the repeated collapse of a sewer and fresh water culvert in the road's narrowest section which is in Petersham, an ordeal referred to as the Petersham Hole.
[src:alcott-house/a307-road] The route has sometimes been used from a few hundred metres south of the Richmond Gate of Richmond Park to Kingston as part of the London-Surrey cycle classic events routes, depending on the availability of Park Road, Kingston which avoids the hairpin and sharper descent at Richmond Gate.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The **A308** is a road in England in two parts.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The first part runs from Central London to Putney Bridge.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The second part runs from just beyond Putney Heath to Bisham, Berkshire.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] It traces four, roughly straight lines, to stay no more than 3 miles (4.8 km) from the Thames.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] It is a dual carriageway where it is furthest from that river, in Spelthorne, Surrey and forms one of the motorway spurs to the large town of Maidenhead.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The South Kensington to Fulham section starts at the A4 road opposite Brompton Oratory and follows Fulham Road south-west past Chelsea and Westminster Hospital, where it jumps south a block to takeover the Kings Road.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] Through broad Fulham which traditionally, as bolstered by its associated London postcode, covers half of the borough, the road becomes New Kings Road, before it ends at the A219 road (Fulham Palace Road), 100m north of Putney Bridge.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The hiatus in the road which is Putney and Putney Heath is a subsumation into the A219 road and then into the A3.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] It runs from Kingston Vale's Robin Hood Gate roundabout.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The entrance to Richmond Park here was closed to motor vehicles in 2003.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The road is named Kingston Vale then Kingston Hill until it falls past Kingston Hospital to becomes London Road.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] Immediately after snaking through central Kingston upon Thames as part of the one-way system, the road passes through a tunnel underneath the John Lewis Kingston department store, before crossing the River Thames at Kingston Bridge where it has another roundabout.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The A308 in this borough is called Hampton Court Road, briefly Thames Street and then Upper Sunbury Road.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The largely straight road from Hampton Court was surfaced and tolled in the 1780s by the Hampton and Staines Turnpike Trust.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] In the west its buildings were set back with gardens and therefore it was widened in Spelthorne in the 1920s.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] As Staines Road East, the A308 winds past Kempton Park Racecourse, Sunbury-on-Thames and adopts instead of south-west followed after Kingston by west, the direction WNW, allowing it to meet Junction 1 of the M3/the A316 at the Sunbury Cross area also within Sunbury on Thames.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] It crosses the M25 motorway, that has a large cross-river junction at Junction 13, north of Egham.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] The road turns north-west, as Windsor Road, in the middle of Runnymede's meadows, with its National Trust buildings and memorials, before leaving Surrey and entering Berkshire.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] In Berkshire, the A308 forms the main road of the town of Old Windsor, where it is called Straight Road.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] It then goes on past the north end of Windsor Great Park, where it is called Albert Road, and through the west side of central Windsor.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] In Windsor, the A308 is called Osborne Road, Goslar Way and Maidenhead Road which finally re-adopts the normal third part-orientation of WNW.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] Finally, after sweeping round to its fourth major direction, NNW through Bray under the M4 (the original location of Junction 8), to a junction with the A308(M) which is a spur connecting to the M4.
[src:alcott-house/a308-road] Facing this on the river is the larger, equally well-preserved and green town of Marlow.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The prime mover behind the community was "sacred socialist" and mystic James Pierrepont Greaves, who was influenced by American transcendentalist Amos Bronson Alcott, and Swiss educational reformer Johann Heinrich Pestalozzi.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] Together with his followers, who included Charles Lane – and with the help of wealthy sponsors, Sophia and Georgiana Chichester – he founded Alcott House on Ham Common in Surrey in 1838.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The Ham Common Concordium, as it came to be known, consisted of a working mixed cooperative community and a progressive school for children.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The headmaster of Alcott House was Henry Gardiner Wright.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The community was dedicated to a regime of spiritual development and purification – in the words of Greaves, aiming to produce the "*most loveful, intelligent and efficient conditions for divine progress in humanity*".
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] To this end the members submitted to an austere regime of early rising, strict vegetarianism (usually raw food), no stimulants, celibacy, and simple living, and experimented with various practices such as astrology, hydrotherapy, mesmerism and phrenology.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The men grew their hair and beards long and wore loose-fitting clothes, while the women defied convention by not wearing the traditional, restrictive corset.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The community at Alcott House promoted a strict vegan diet, all meals were served cold apart from hot potatoes.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] Alcott House rejected all animal source foods including meat, butter, cheese, eggs and all stimulants such as chocolate, coffee, tea as well as mustard, salt, vinegar and spices.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] Alcott House school was open to children from both inside and outside the community – the latter usually from radical parents who sympathised with its progressive educational stance.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The curriculum emphasised moral education and the development of the child's innate spiritual gifts, teaching practical skills such as gardening and cookery as well as book learning.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] Punishment was frowned upon and education aimed to produce "*integral men and women*", able to live in a truly cooperative society and not simply playing traditional roles.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] In 1848, the community came to an end and the house was purchased in 1849 by John Minter Morgan to provide an orphanage for 70 children, the National Orphan Home for Girls, though still run along vegetarian lines.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] In 1856 the foundation stone was laid for the present building, **South Lodge**, opened in 1862, which could accommodate 200 children in the National Orphan Home for Girls.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] It is of "yellow brick, Late Classical, with a central turret in the Italiane style".
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] South Lodge has been converted to flats and the grounds have been developed as Bishops Close.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The British and Foreign Society for the Promotion of Humanity and Abstinence from Animal Food was formed at Alcott House by a group of vegetarians in 1843.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] Unlike other organisations during this time, the Society had an open membership for women and let them hold office.
[src:alcott-house/alcott-house] The Society has been described as the world's first vegetarian organisation, and as a forerunner to the Vegetarian Society.
